This house believes that “Operation Yukthiya” has done more harm than good

Operation Yukthiya is an ongoing island-wide anti-drug operation conducted by the Sri Lankan Police, Army, and Special Task Force. Launched in December 2023, the operation consists of a series of island-wide raids, mass arrests, seizures of firearms and illicit substances, and the detention of hundreds in military-run rehabilitation centers.


As of January 17th, 38,525 suspects (including 65% of ‘key individuals’ involved in narcotics distribution) have been arrested, and illegal drugs valued at approximately 4.7 billion have been seized. The street-level price of drugs has reportedly increased up to sevenfold. Minister of Public Security Tiran Alles has also stated that crime rates across the country fell by 17% within the first month of the operation.


However, this operation has faced significant backlash for its punitive and militarized approach to drug control. Organizations including the UN Human Rights Commission have drawn attention to reports of human rights violations conducted by police and army personnel.


These include alleged arbitrary arrests, primarily targeting individuals from marginalized socio-economic communities; degrading treatment, including strip searches in public; and the televising of searches and arrests in violation of the right to privacy of detainees. Military-run rehabilitation centers have also been criticized for focusing on strenuous physical exercise and for the lack of trained professionals to monitor the health of detainees.
